+# Pluggable Malloc Backends for glibc
+
+## Overview
+
+This patch adds a build-time `--with-malloc=IMPL` configure switch to glibc
+that selects the malloc implementation compiled into `libc.so`. It is modelled
+after musl's build-time choice between its legacy `malloc` and `mallocng`.
+
+A single implementation name keeps the historical **zero runtime dispatch
+overhead** path embedded in `libc.so`.  Passing a comma-separated list embeds
+only `--with-default-malloc` (default: first name) in libc and builds the
+other names as `$libdir/glibc/malloc/libglibc_malloc_<name>.so`, discovered
+at runtime from installed files (distros can subpackage them).  Selection
+values are **preference lists** (`snmalloc,rpmalloc,*`) tried in order.
+`GLIBC_MALLOC_IMPL` is honored by `ld.so` before `__rtld_malloc_init_real`
+so the chosen DSO is mapped with the initial link graph.  See
+[Multi-implementation builds](#multi-implementation-builds).
+
+Currently supported values:
+
+| Value              | Description                              |
+|--------------------|------------------------------------------|
+| `glibc`            | (default) Traditional ptmalloc2-based allocator |
+| `mimalloc`         | Microsoft's mimalloc, compiled in-tree from `malloc/mimalloc/` |
+| `mimalloc-secure`  | Same mimalloc sources with `MI_SECURE=4` (guard pages, encoded freelists, double-free checks); symbols renamed so it can coexist with `mimalloc` |
+| `jemalloc`         | Facebook/Meta's jemalloc, compiled in-tree from `malloc/jemalloc/` |
+| `snmalloc`         | Microsoft Research's snmalloc, compiled in-tree from `malloc/snmalloc/` |
+| `rpmalloc`         | Rampant Pixels' rpmalloc, compiled in-tree from `malloc/rpmalloc/` |
+| `mallocng`         | musl libc's mallocng, compiled in-tree from `malloc/mallocng/` |
+| `hardened-malloc`  | GrapheneOS hardened_malloc, under `malloc/hardened_malloc/` |
+| `phasecast`        | In-tree adaptive phase-cast allocator (`malloc/phasecast/`) |
+
+**Not embeddable in `libc.so`** (they need libstdc++, which depends on libc's
+malloc — linking them into libc would be circular):
+
+| Preload DSO | Configure | Use |
+|-------------|-----------|-----|
+| `libglibc_malloc_partitionalloc.so` | `--with-malloc-preload=partitionalloc` | `LD_PRELOAD=.../libglibc_malloc_partitionalloc.so` |
+| `libglibc_malloc_mesh.so` | `--with-malloc-preload=mesh` | `LD_PRELOAD=.../libglibc_malloc_mesh.so` |
+| `libglibc_malloc_tcmalloc.so` | `--with-malloc-preload=tcmalloc` | `LD_PRELOAD=.../libglibc_malloc_tcmalloc.so` (full gperftools libtcmalloc with heap profiler) |
+
+Configure tokens for embedded impls may contain `-` (valid in `malloc.conf` /
+`GLIBC_MALLOC_IMPL`); C symbols map `-` to `_`.
+
+## How to Use
+
+### Building with the default allocator (no change)
+
+```sh
+mkdir build && cd build
+../configure --prefix=/opt/glibc
+make -j$(nproc)
+```
+
+### Building with mimalloc
+
+```sh
+mkdir build-mi && cd build-mi
+../configure --prefix=/opt/glibc-mi --with-malloc=mimalloc --disable-werror
+make -j$(nproc)
+```
+
+mimalloc is compiled directly into `libc.so` from the in-tree source copy
+at `malloc/mimalloc/`.  **No external source tree or build step is
+required.**  The C amalgamation (`malloc/malloc-mimalloc-impl.c`) includes
+`mimalloc/src/static.c` and is linked alongside the C shim
+(`malloc/malloc-mimalloc.c`).
+
+### Building with mimalloc-secure
+
+```sh
+mkdir build-mis && cd build-mis
+../configure --prefix=/opt/glibc-mis --with-malloc=mimalloc-secure --disable-werror
+make -j$(nproc)
+```
+
+Reuses `malloc/mimalloc/` compiled with `-DMI_SECURE=4`.  Exported symbols
+are renamed (`mi_*` → `mis_*`) via `malloc-mimalloc-secure-rename.h` so a
+multi build can embed both `mimalloc` and `mimalloc-secure`.  Overhead is
+modest versus plain mimalloc (encoded freelists, double-free checks, guard
+pages around metadata).
+
+### Building with jemalloc
+
+```sh
+mkdir build-je && cd build-je
+../configure --prefix=/opt/glibc-je --with-malloc=jemalloc --disable-werror
+make -j$(nproc)
+```
+
+jemalloc is compiled directly into `libc.so` from the in-tree source copy
+at `malloc/jemalloc/`.  **No external build step or pre-built static
+library is required.**  Configure-generated headers are vendored alongside
+the sources (configured with `--with-jemalloc-prefix=je_`).  Individual
+translation units under `malloc/jemalloc/src/` are compiled by
+`malloc/Makefile` and linked with the C shim (`malloc/malloc-jemalloc.c`).
+
+
+### Building with snmalloc
+
+```sh
+mkdir build-sn && cd build-sn
+../configure --prefix=/opt/glibc-sn --with-malloc=snmalloc --disable-werror
+make -j$(nproc)
+```
+
+snmalloc is compiled directly into `libc.so` from the in-tree source copy
+at `malloc/snmalloc/`.  **No external build step, no CMake dependency, and
+no `libstdc++` runtime dependency** are required.  snmalloc's own vendored
+STL replacements (`SNMALLOC_USE_SELF_VENDORED_STL`) and direct use of
+glibc's `__cxa_thread_atexit_impl` eliminate the need for a C++ standard
+library at runtime.
+
+The C++ core (`malloc/malloc-snmalloc-impl.cc`) is compiled with
+`-fno-exceptions -fno-rtti -nostdlib` semantics and linked into `libc.so`
+alongside the C shim (`malloc/malloc-snmalloc.c`).
+
+### Building with rpmalloc
+
+```sh
+mkdir build-rp && cd build-rp
+../configure --prefix=/opt/glibc-rp --with-malloc=rpmalloc --disable-werror
+make -j$(nproc)
+```
+
+rpmalloc is compiled directly into `libc.so` from the in-tree source copy
+at `malloc/rpmalloc/`.  **No external source tree is required.**  The core
+allocator (`malloc/malloc-rpmalloc-impl.c` with `ENABLE_OVERRIDE=0`) is
+linked alongside the C shim (`malloc/malloc-rpmalloc.c`).  The upstream
+system-override layer (`malloc.c`) is intentionally omitted.
+
+
+### Building with mallocng
+
+```sh
+mkdir build-ng && cd build-ng
+../configure --prefix=/opt/glibc-ng --with-malloc=mallocng --disable-werror
+make -j$(nproc)
+```
+
+mallocng is compiled directly into `libc.so` from the in-tree source copy
+at `malloc/mallocng/`.  **No external source tree is required.**  A
+replacement glue layer re-implements the musl internals mallocng needs
+(atomics, locks, `brk`, randomness) using GCC builtins and POSIX APIs.
+The core (`malloc/malloc-mallocng-impl.c`) is linked alongside the C shim
+(`malloc/malloc-mallocng.c`).
+
+### Building PartitionAlloc / Mesh preload DSOs
+
+These allocators are written in C++ and use the C++ standard library.  They
+**must not** be linked into `libc.so` (libstdc++ calls `malloc`, so that
+would be a circular dependency).  Build standalone interposition DSOs:
+
+```sh
+../configure --prefix=/usr --disable-werror   --with-malloc-preload=partitionalloc,mesh,tcmalloc
+make -j$(nproc)
+# installs libglibc_malloc_{partitionalloc,mesh,tcmalloc}.so
+```
+
+```sh
+LD_PRELOAD=/usr/lib64/libglibc_malloc_partitionalloc.so mydaemon
+LD_PRELOAD=/usr/lib64/libglibc_malloc_mesh.so long-running-service
+```
+
+Sources live under `malloc/partition_alloc/` (Chromium `main`),
+`malloc/mesh/` (plasma-umass Mesh + Heap-Layers), and `malloc/tcmalloc/`
+(gperftools libtcmalloc with sampling/heap profiler; not `tcmalloc_minimal`).
+
+
+### Building with hardened-malloc
+
+```sh
+mkdir build-hm && cd build-hm
+../configure --prefix=/opt/glibc-hm --with-malloc=hardened-malloc --disable-werror
+make -j$(nproc)
+```
+
+GrapheneOS hardened_malloc compiled as one amalgamation TU
+(`malloc-hardened-malloc-impl.c`) with `-DH_MALLOC_PREFIX` and
+`-DMALLOC_EMBEDDED_IN_LIBC` (registers fork handlers via
+`__register_atfork`).  Self-init is disabled so multi builds do not reserve
+slab VA until the backend is selected.  Useful for network-facing daemons
+when the security mitigations outweigh the throughput cost.
+
+### Building with phasecast
+
+```sh
+mkdir build-pc && cd build-pc
+../configure --prefix=/opt/glibc-pc --with-malloc=phasecast --disable-werror
+make -j$(nproc)
+```
+
+Phasecast is an in-tree adaptive allocator (`malloc/phasecast/`) that routes
+each allocation site (return PC × size class) through a direct function
+pointer after a short warmup.  Per-thread size-class caches feed a central
+span heap; optional `gnu_malloc_phase_push` / `gnu_malloc_phase_pop` markers
+switch the calling thread into an ephemeral bump arena reclaimed on pop.
+Profile load/save (`gnu_malloc_phase_{load,save}_profile`) can pre-specialize
+hot sites across runs.  The core is compiled by `malloc-phasecast-impl.c`
+alongside the C shim `malloc-phasecast.c`.  No external sources required.
+
+**Status:** MVP with overflow-safe sizing, payload-aligned size-class spans
+(so `memalign` reuses cached slots up to 128-byte alignment), and full
+`size_t` usable sizes.  `make check GLIBC_MALLOC_IMPL=phasecast` skips
+ptmalloc2-only tests automatically and injects the impl into ordinary test
+envs (dynamic selector tests keep their own `*-ENV`).  On a mixed alloc/free
+microbench the embeddable incumbents (snmalloc, rpmalloc) and tcmalloc preload
+still win raw throughput; phasecast’s bet is workload-phase specialization
+(ephemeral arenas + PGO site profiles), which needs real compile/server traces
+to validate.
+
+
+## Multi-implementation builds
+
+Embed several allocators in one `libc.so` and choose among them at startup:
+
+```sh
+mkdir build-multi && cd build-multi
+../configure --prefix=/usr \
+  --with-malloc=glibc,mimalloc,snmalloc,rpmalloc \
+  --with-default-malloc=rpmalloc \
+  --disable-werror
+make -j$(nproc)
+```
+
+Configure variables written to `config.make`:
+
+| Variable          | Single build     | Multi build                          |
+|-------------------|------------------|--------------------------------------|
+| `malloc-impl`     | `mimalloc` etc.  | `multi`                              |
+| `malloc-impls`    | one name         | space-separated enabled names        |
+| `malloc-default`  | that name        | `--with-default-malloc` or first     |
+| `malloc-multi`    | `no`             | `yes`                                |
+
+Duplicates in `--with-malloc` are rejected.  `--with-default-malloc` must
+name one of the enabled implementations.
+
+### Runtime selection order
+
+`malloc/malloc-select.c` runs once on first allocation (latched).  Highest
+effective priority wins; unavailable names are ignored and selection
+falls through.  Setuid/setgid processes (`__libc_enable_secure`) skip
+env/drop-ins/heuristics entirely.
+
+1. **External interposition** — if public `malloc` is not defined by
+   `libc.so*`, report `"external"` from `gnu_get_libc_malloc_active()`.
+   Internal `__libc_*` entry points still bind to the compile-time default.
+2. **`GLIBC_MALLOC_IMPL=pref-list`** environment variable (e.g.
+   `snmalloc,rpmalloc,*`).  Honored by `ld.so` before the real malloc
+   handoff; ignored under `AT_SECURE`.
+3. **`GLIBC_MALLOC_CONF=path`** — optional non-secure override for the
+   conf file consulted for `default=` (defaults to
+   `/etc/glibc/malloc.conf`).  Intended for tests and images that keep
+   policy outside `/etc`.
+4. **`/etc/glibc/malloc.conf` per-basename lines** (`clang,clang++=mimalloc`)
+   — user/admin overrides; always beat drop-in files.
+5. **`/etc/glibc/malloc.d/*.conf`** — admin/local drop-ins.
+6. **`/etc/glibc/malloc.conf` `default=pref-list`** — overrides distro
+   drop-ins and heuristics when no higher rule matched (so a user whose
+   workload disagrees with distro tuning can reset the fallback without
+   deleting package snippets).  `ld.so` applies this same `default=`
+   line when mapping an early dynamic backend.
+
+6. **`DATADIR/glibc/malloc.d/*.conf`** — distro-provided drop-ins
+   (arch-independent; typically `/usr/share/glibc/malloc.d`).
+7. **Heuristics** — toolchain binaries prefer `snmalloc` then `rpmalloc`;
+   GUI-linked binaries (Qt/GTK/X11/Wayland/SDL SONAME scan) prefer
+   `mimalloc` then `glibc`.
+8. **Compile-time default** (`--with-default-malloc`), else the first
+   backend in the configure list.
+
+Drop-in `priority=` only orders files inside the same directory tier and
+is clamped to `0..99` (default `50`), so distro snippets cannot outrank
+`/etc/glibc/malloc.conf`.  Equal effective priorities resolve by
+lexicographically smaller source path.
+
+After selection the hot path is a single acquire-load of the active
+backend pointer.  Selection uses small stack buffers, `__getdents64`, and
+non-allocating link-map checks; the final backend is published once after
+`init`.  Under `AT_SECURE`, query APIs report only the compile-time default.
+
+### Drop-in configuration format
+
+Install package tuning under `DATADIR/glibc/malloc.d/` (shared across
+CPU architectures; availability fallback ignores `impl=` names not
+embedded in that arch's libc).  Put user overrides in
+`/etc/glibc/malloc.conf` or `/etc/glibc/malloc.d/`.
+
+```
+priority=50
+match-basename=clang,clang++,clang-20,clang++-20
+impl=snmalloc
+```
+
+`/etc/glibc/malloc.conf` example:
+
+```
+clang,clang++=mimalloc
+default=rpmalloc
+```
+
+| Key               | Meaning                                      |
+|-------------------|----------------------------------------------|
+| `priority=N`      | in-tier order only, `0..99` (default `50`)   |
+| `impl=NAME`       | backend name (required)                      |
+| `match-basename=` | match `/proc/self/exe` basename against any comma-separated entry (`clang,clang++`); repeat the key on more lines to OR further names |
+| `match-path=`     | match full executable path against any comma-separated entry (same OR semantics) |
+
+Whitespace around commas is ignored.  Basename entries are restricted to
+`[A-Za-z0-9._+-]`; empty entries invalidate the file.  Multiple
+`match-*` lines in one file are OR'd.
+
+A file without `match-*` rules matches every process.  Sample docs are
+installed as `/etc/glibc/malloc.d/README`.
+
+### Public query API
+
+Declared in `<malloc.h>` and exported at `GLIBC_2.44`:
+
+```c
+int gnu_get_libc_malloc_impls (char *buf, size_t len);
+const char *gnu_get_libc_malloc_default (void);
+const char *gnu_get_libc_malloc_active (void);
+```
+
+`gnu_get_libc_malloc_impls` writes a comma-separated list of embedded names.
+`gnu_get_libc_malloc_active` returns `"external"` when malloc is interposed.
+
+### `glibc-malloc-profile`
+
+Installed to `bindir` on multi-impl builds.  Runs a **representative**
+command under each implementation via `GLIBC_MALLOC_IMPL`, measures
+average wall time (discarding non-zero exits), and can write a drop-in.
+Pass the same arguments the application sees in production — profiling
+`grep` with no operands is not meaningful compared to e.g.
+`grep -r printf /usr/include`.  Package builds should invoke the tool
+explicitly from a `%check` script or manual tuning pass with real
+workloads; there is no automatic brp hook, because few binaries expose a
+useful default invocation.
+
+```sh
+glibc-malloc-profile --output=/etc/glibc/malloc.d/clang.conf -- \
+  clang -O2 -c hello.c
+
+glibc-malloc-profile --output=/etc/glibc/malloc.d/grep.conf -- \
+  grep -r printf /usr/include
+```
+
+Options: `--impls=list`, `--runs=N`, `--warmup=N`, `--margin=PCT`,
+`--libc-dir=DIR` (run via that tree's `ld.so` / `libc.so.6`).
+Interactive commands are refused.  If the winner is the compile-time
+default (or the margin threshold is not met), no file is written.
+
