+
+## How to Plug in Another Malloc Implementation
+
+To add a new backend, follow these steps. You can use any of the existing
+shim files as a template: any of `malloc-mimalloc.c`,
+`malloc-jemalloc.c`, `malloc-snmalloc.c`, `malloc-rpmalloc.c`, or
+`malloc-mallocng.c`, plus a matching in-tree source directory under
+`malloc/<backend>/`.
+
+### 1. Register the name in `configure.ac`
+
+In `configure.ac`, add your implementation name to the `case` statement:
+
+```
+case "$malloc_impl" in
+  glibc)     ;;
+  mimalloc)  ;;
+  mymalloc)  ;;                    # <-- add here
+  *)
+    AC_MSG_ERROR([--with-malloc only accepts glibc, mimalloc, or mymalloc])
+    ;;
+esac
+```
+
+Regenerate `configure` (requires autoconf 2.72) or hand-edit the
+equivalent block in the `configure` script.
+
+### 2. Create the shim source file
+
+Create `malloc/malloc-YOURNAME.c`. This file must:
+
+1. **Include your allocator's sources** (either `#include` a
+   single-compilation-unit file, or compile separately and link).
+
+2. **Define these functions** (the glibc-internal malloc API):
+
+   | Function | Signature |
+   |----------|-----------|
+   | `__libc_malloc` | `void *__libc_malloc(size_t)` |
+   | `__libc_free` | `void __libc_free(void *)` |
+   | `__libc_realloc` | `void *__libc_realloc(void *, size_t)` |
+   | `__libc_calloc` | `void *__libc_calloc(size_t, size_t)` |
+   | `__libc_memalign` | `void *__libc_memalign(size_t, size_t)` |
+   | `__libc_valloc` | `void *__libc_valloc(size_t)` |
+   | `__libc_pvalloc` | `void *__libc_pvalloc(size_t)` |
+   | `__posix_memalign` | `int __posix_memalign(void **, size_t, size_t)` |
+   | `aligned_alloc` | `void *aligned_alloc(size_t, size_t)` (weak) |
+   | `free_sized` | `void free_sized(void *, size_t)` (weak) |
+   | `free_aligned_sized` | `void free_aligned_sized(void *, size_t, size_t)` (weak) |
+   | `__malloc_usable_size` | `size_t __malloc_usable_size(void *)` |
+   | `__libc_mallopt` | `int __libc_mallopt(int, int)` (can return 1) |
+   | `__libc_mallinfo` | `struct mallinfo __libc_mallinfo(void)` (can return zeros) |
+   | `__libc_mallinfo2` | `struct mallinfo2 __libc_mallinfo2(void)` (can return zeros) |
+   | `__malloc_info` | `int __malloc_info(int, FILE *)` (stub OK) |
+   | `__malloc_stats` | `void __malloc_stats(void)` (stub OK) |
+   | `__malloc_trim` | `int __malloc_trim(size_t)` (stub OK) |
+
+3. **Define these internal hooks** (called by pthreads / fork):
+
+   | Function | Purpose |
+   |----------|---------|
+   | `__malloc_fork_lock_parent` | Called before `fork()` |
+   | `__malloc_fork_unlock_parent` | Called after `fork()` in parent |
+   | `__malloc_fork_unlock_child` | Called after `fork()` in child |
+   | `__malloc_arena_thread_freeres` | Called on thread exit |
+   | `__malloc_check_init` | Debug-mode init (can be empty) |
+   | `__ptmalloc_init` | Early init (can be empty if self-initializing) |
+
+4. **Provide hidden-symbol declarations and definitions** using
+   `libc_hidden_proto` / `libc_hidden_def` for functions that the rest of
+   glibc calls internally (see `malloc-mimalloc.c` for the exact set).
+
+5. **Provide the public-symbol aliases** at the bottom:
+
+   ```c
+   #if IS_IN (libc)
+   strong_alias (__libc_malloc, malloc)
+   strong_alias (__libc_realloc, realloc)
+   strong_alias (__libc_free, free)
+   weak_alias (__libc_calloc, calloc)
+   weak_alias (__libc_memalign, memalign)
+   weak_alias (__posix_memalign, posix_memalign)
+   weak_alias (__libc_valloc, valloc)
+   weak_alias (__libc_pvalloc, pvalloc)
+   weak_alias (__malloc_usable_size, malloc_usable_size)
+   /* ... plus mallinfo, mallopt, malloc_stats, malloc_trim, malloc_info */
+   #endif
+   ```
+
+6. **Provide compat symbols**:
+
+   ```c
+   #if SHLIB_COMPAT (libc, GLIBC_2_0, GLIBC_2_26)
+   compat_symbol (libc, __libc_free, cfree, GLIBC_2_0);
+   #endif
+   #if SHLIB_COMPAT (libc, GLIBC_2_0, GLIBC_2_34)
+   compat_symbol (libc, __glibc_morecore, __default_morecore, GLIBC_2_0);
+   #endif
+   ```
+
+7. **Provide the deprecated hook variables** (can be NULL):
+
+   ```c
+   void *__malloc_initialize_hook = NULL;
+   void *__free_hook = NULL;
+   void *__malloc_hook = NULL;
+   void *__realloc_hook = NULL;
+   void *__memalign_hook = NULL;
+   void *__after_morecore_hook = NULL;
+   void *__morecore = NULL;
+   ```
+
+Use `malloc/malloc-mimalloc.c` as a complete reference implementation.
+
+### 3. Wire it into the Makefile
+
+In `malloc/Makefile`, add a clause to the `malloc-routines` selection:
+
+```makefile
+ifeq ($(malloc-impl),mymalloc)
+malloc-routines = malloc-mymalloc
+else ifeq ($(malloc-impl),mimalloc)
+malloc-routines = malloc-mimalloc
+else
+malloc-routines = malloc
+endif
+```
+
+Add `CPPFLAGS-malloc-mymalloc.c` entries with include paths and any
+defines your allocator needs.
+
+### 4. Build and test
+
+```sh
+mkdir build && cd build
+../configure --with-malloc=mymalloc --disable-werror
+make -j$(nproc)
+
+# Smoke test
+./elf/ld.so --library-path .:math:elf /path/to/test_program
+
+# Run malloc benchmarks
+make subdirs=benchtests bench-build BENCHSET="malloc-simple malloc-thread"
+```
+
+---
+
+## Architecture
+
+```
+configure --with-malloc=IMPL
+        │
+        ▼
+  config.make: malloc-impl = IMPL
+        │
+        ▼
+  malloc/Makefile
+    ┌────────────────────────────────────────┐
+    │ Select malloc-routines based on        │
+    │ malloc-impl; set CPPFLAGS per impl     │
+    └────────────────────────────────────────┘
+        │
+        ▼
+  malloc-mimalloc.c (+ impl)   C shim → malloc/mimalloc/ (in-tree)
+  malloc-jemalloc.c (+ src/*)  C shim → malloc/jemalloc/ (in-tree)
+  malloc-snmalloc.c (+ impl)   C shim → malloc/snmalloc/ (C++, in-tree)
+  malloc-rpmalloc.c (+ impl)   C shim → malloc/rpmalloc/ (in-tree)
+  malloc-mallocng.c (+ impl)   C shim → malloc/mallocng/ (in-tree)
+  malloc.c                     Stock ptmalloc2 (default)
+        │
+        ▼
+      libc.so.6 / libc.a
+```
+
+The key design principle is that **only the core allocator object changes**.
+All other malloc-subdirectory files (`mcheck.c`, `mtrace.c`, `obstack.c`,
+`reallocarray.c`, etc.) are shared between backends and call through the
+public `malloc`/`free`/`realloc` symbols, which resolve to whichever
+backend was selected.
+
+---
+
+## Limitations and Future Work
+
+- **mallinfo / mallinfo2**: Non-glibc shims return zeroed structs.
+  A more complete integration could map each allocator's statistics to
+  these fields (jemalloc has `je_malloc_stats_print`, mimalloc has
+  `mi_stats_print`).
+- **malloc_info**: The XML output is minimal for non-glibc backends.
+  Could be extended to emit allocator-specific data.
+- **MALLOC_CHECK_ / libc_malloc_debug.so**: The debug malloc library
+  (`libc_malloc_debug.so`) is always built from the original `malloc.c`
+  code. It is designed for LD_PRELOAD use and is independent of the
+  selected backend.
+- **Tunables**: glibc's `GLIBC_TUNABLES` malloc knobs (e.g.,
+  `glibc.malloc.tcache_count`) are specific to ptmalloc2 and have no
+  effect when alternative backends are selected. Each allocator has its
+  own environment variable controls (`MIMALLOC_*`, `JE_MALLOC_CONF`, etc.).
+- **snmalloc C++ compilation**: snmalloc is compiled as C++17 with
+  `-fno-exceptions -fno-rtti` and uses self-vendored STL replacements,
+  so it has no runtime dependency on `libstdc++`.  The C++ compiler
+  (`g++` or `clang++`) is required at build time.
+- **Updating vendored allocators**: Each in-tree copy under
+  `malloc/<backend>/` should be refreshed from upstream when upgrading.
+  jemalloc additionally needs its configure-generated headers regenerated
+  (see `malloc/jemalloc/README.md`).
+- **mallocng thread scaling**: mallocng uses a single global lock, making
+  it unsuitable for heavily multi-threaded workloads. It is best suited
+  for embedded or single-threaded environments.
+- **Static linking**: All backends are compiled into `libc.a` directly.
+  The weak stubs in `elf/static-stubs.c` allow libgcc_eh to be linked
+  when needed (e.g. by unwinding paths pulled in transitively).
