+# Malloc Backend Benchmark Report
+
+## Test Environment
+
+- **CPU**: x86_64, nproc = 32
+- **Kernel**: Linux 7.0.10-server-gcc-1omv2690
+- **Compiler**: GCC 16.1.1
+- **glibc**: malloc-experiments branch with fully in-tree pluggable backends
+- **Benchmarks**:
+  1. Synthetic workloads (small / large / mixed / realloc / 4-thread), 3 runs, median reported
+  2. `benchtests/bench-malloc-simple` (hp_timing ticks/iter, lower is better)
+  3. `benchtests/bench-malloc-thread` (3s mixed workload, time/iter + max RSS)
+- Each backend built with `../configure --prefix=/usr --disable-werror --disable-mathvec --with-malloc=IMPL`
+- Benchmarks executed via each build's `testrun.sh` so the under-test `libc.so` is used
+
+## Backends Tested
+
+| Backend | Integration | libc.so size |
+|---------|-------------|-------------:|
+| **glibc** | Native ptmalloc2 (default) | 11,674 KB |
+| **mimalloc** | In-tree `malloc/mimalloc/` | 12,241 KB |
+| **jemalloc** | In-tree `malloc/jemalloc/` | 15,162 KB |
+| **snmalloc** | In-tree `malloc/snmalloc/` (C++) | 14,454 KB |
+| **rpmalloc** | In-tree `malloc/rpmalloc/` | 11,633 KB |
+| **mallocng** | In-tree `malloc/mallocng/` | 11,579 KB |
+
+## Synthetic Workloads
+
+### Throughput (Mops/s — higher is better, median of 3 runs)
+
+| Benchmark | glibc | mimalloc | jemalloc | snmalloc | rpmalloc | mallocng |
+|-----------|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|
+| **Small alloc** (8–256 B, 2M ops) | 538.99 | 544.77 | 578.37 | 621.75 | **623.20** | 618.58 |
+| **Large alloc** (4 KB–1 MB, 200K ops) | 0.09 | 1.88 | 1.35 | **4.28** | 3.60 | 0.12 |
+| **Mixed alloc** (8 B–64 KB, 1M ops) | 4.22 | 22.16 | 3.80 | 48.47 | **60.43** | 1.05 |
+| **Realloc** (500K ops) | 28.43 | 15.92 | 17.54 | 27.37 | **80.55** | 5.63 |
+| **MT 4-thread** (8M ops) | 304.16 | 278.59 | 311.31 | 334.24 | **380.54** | 7.20 |
+
+### Execution Time (seconds — lower is better, median of 3 runs)
+
+| Benchmark | glibc | mimalloc | jemalloc | snmalloc | rpmalloc | mallocng |
+|-----------|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|
+| **Small alloc** (8–256 B, 2M ops) | 0.0037 | 0.0037 | 0.0035 | **0.0032** | 0.0032 | 0.0032 |
+| **Large alloc** (4 KB–1 MB, 200K ops) | 2.2569 | 0.1062 | 0.1483 | **0.0467** | 0.0555 | 1.6173 |
+| **Mixed alloc** (8 B–64 KB, 1M ops) | 0.2368 | 0.0451 | 0.2631 | 0.0206 | **0.0165** | 0.9510 |
+| **Realloc** (500K ops) | 0.0176 | 0.0314 | 0.0285 | 0.0183 | **0.0062** | 0.0888 |
+| **MT 4-thread** (8M ops) | 0.0263 | 0.0287 | 0.0257 | 0.0239 | **0.0210** | 1.1117 |
+
+### Peak RSS (KB — lower is better, median of 3 runs)
+
+| Metric | glibc | mimalloc | jemalloc | snmalloc | rpmalloc | mallocng |
+|--------|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|
+| **Peak RSS** | 37,264 | 69,328 | 98,088 | 69,376 | 140,824 | **16,912** |
+
+## bench-malloc-simple (16-byte blocks, hp_timing ticks/iter — lower is better)
+
+| Scenario | glibc | mimalloc | jemalloc | snmalloc | rpmalloc | mallocng |
+|----------|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|
+| ST 25 | 38.59 | 23.28 | 16.31 | 27.63 | **13.47** | 71.69 |
+| ST 400 | 96.95 | 22.77 | 34.22 | 22.99 | **13.36** | 210.86 |
+| ST 1600 | 100.21 | 22.91 | 38.51 | 23.60 | **13.46** | 160.79 |
+| MT 25 | 56.70 | 23.31 | 16.76 | 24.30 | **13.84** | 58.03 |
+| MT 1600 | 103.76 | 23.45 | 38.88 | 22.70 | **13.34** | 162.58 |
+| Thread 25 | 56.36 | 24.73 | 17.39 | 26.20 | **14.33** | 60.45 |
+| Thread 1600 | 105.35 | 22.87 | 39.45 | 23.19 | **13.43** | 160.38 |
+| max_rss KB | 3,524 | 5,596 | 10,008 | 5,528 | 7,644 | **3,300** |
+
+## bench-malloc-thread (3s mixed 4–32768 B workload, 1 thread)
+
+| Metric | glibc | mimalloc | jemalloc | snmalloc | rpmalloc | mallocng |
+|--------|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|---------:|
+| time/iter (ns) | 23.63 | **16.34** | 22.29 | 24.33 | 18.87 | 114.40 |
+| max_rss (KB) | **3,612** | 6,208 | 8,472 | 6,148 | 12,348 | 3,696 |
+
+## Summary
+
+- **rpmalloc** leads `bench-malloc-simple` by a wide margin (~13 ticks vs ~23+ for others) and dominates synthetic realloc (~81 Mops/s) and mixed alloc throughput.
+- **snmalloc** is strongest on synthetic large-alloc throughput and very strong on mixed alloc; competitive multi-threaded scaling.
+- **mimalloc** is consistently fast on small/mixed workloads with stable RSS behaviour in `bench-malloc-simple`.
+- **jemalloc** is solid on small allocs in `bench-malloc-simple` but loses on mixed synthetic workloads; largest `libc.so`.
+- **glibc ptmalloc2** has the lowest peak RSS in the synthetic suite but is far slower on large/mixed allocations.
+- **mallocng** is compact and fine for tiny single-thread allocs, but its single global lock makes multi-threaded and mixed workloads poor fits.
+
+### Recommendations (embeddable in-tree backends only)
+
+| Use case | Recommendation | Rationale |
+|----------|----------------|-----------|
+| General / containers | **snmalloc** or **rpmalloc** | Best overall throughput; small libc growth |
+| Realloc-heavy / games | **rpmalloc** | ~3–5× realloc throughput vs alternatives |
+| Multi-threaded servers | **snmalloc** / **jemalloc** | Strong MT results; avoid mallocng |
+| RSS-sensitive embedded | **glibc** or **mallocng** | Lowest peak RSS; accept throughput tradeoff |
+
+Raw logs: `/tmp/malloc-bench/results/`.
+
+---
+
+## Real-world: compiling with clang under each libc
+
+### Setup
+
+- **Compiler**: OpenMandriva clang 22.1.8
+- **Workload**:
+  1. `clang -O2 -c sqlite3.c` (SQLite amalgamation, 257,679 lines) — single process
+  2. `clang -O3 -c sqlite3.c` — single process, heavier optimisations
+  3. `make -j16` building 16 SQLite variants + mimalloc `static.c` + rpmalloc + snmalloc C++ impl
+  4. Same multi-file set with `make -j1` (no compiler parallelism)
+- Each `clang`/`clang++` invocation wrapped with the under-test `ld.so` and `libc.so` from `/tmp/glibc-malloc-build/<impl>` (verified via `/proc/<pid>/maps`)
+- Wall time and peak RSS summed across the make/clang process tree; 3 runs with median unless noted
+
+### SQLite amalgamation `-O2` (median of 3)
+
+| Backend | Time (s) | vs glibc | Peak RSS (MB) |
+|---------|---------:|---------:|--------------:|
+| **glibc** | 12.718 | 1.00x | **228.8** |
+| **mimalloc** | 11.476 | 1.11x | 246.8 |
+| **jemalloc** | 11.620 | 1.09x | 255.7 |
+| **snmalloc** | **11.373** | 1.12x | 273.6 |
+| **rpmalloc** | 11.566 | 1.10x | 318.9 |
+| **mallocng** | 13.765 | 0.92x | 241.0 |
+
+### SQLite amalgamation `-O3` (median of 3)
+
+| Backend | Time (s) | vs glibc | Peak RSS (MB) |
+|---------|---------:|---------:|--------------:|
+| **glibc** | 30.368 | 1.00x | **233.2** |
+| **mimalloc** | 29.920 | 1.01x | 250.6 |
+| **jemalloc** | 22.893 | 1.33x | 255.8 |
+| **snmalloc** | 17.198 | 1.77x | 273.6 |
+| **rpmalloc** | **12.179** | 2.49x | 324.4 |
+| **mallocng** | 14.449 | 2.10x | 245.4 |
+
+### Multi-file compile `make -j16` (median of 3)
+
+| Backend | Time (s) | vs glibc | Peak RSS (MB) |
+|---------|---------:|---------:|--------------:|
+| **glibc** | 17.758 | 1.00x | **3570.0** |
+| **mimalloc** | 16.627 | 1.07x | 3844.1 |
+| **jemalloc** | 16.343 | 1.09x | 3942.5 |
+| **snmalloc** | **16.257** | 1.09x | 4227.9 |
+| **rpmalloc** | 16.559 | 1.07x | 4977.3 |
+| **mallocng** | 19.807 | 0.90x | 3778.8 |
+
+### Multi-file compile `make -j1` (1 run)
+
+| Backend | Time (s) | vs glibc | Peak RSS (MB) |
+|---------|---------:|---------:|--------------:|
+| **glibc** | 199.021 | 1.00x | **231.9** |
+| **mimalloc** | 182.457 | 1.09x | 248.8 |
+| **jemalloc** | 182.235 | 1.09x | 256.6 |
+| **snmalloc** | **181.640** | 1.10x | 273.9 |
+| **rpmalloc** | 182.939 | 1.09x | 319.7 |
+| **mallocng** | 225.100 | 0.88x | 246.5 |
+
+### Observations
+
+- On single-process `-O2` SQLite, **snmalloc**, **mimalloc**, **jemalloc**, and **rpmalloc** cluster around **11.4–11.6 s** (~9–12% faster than ptmalloc2 at 12.7 s). **mallocng** is slowest at ~13.8 s.
+- The `-O3` run amplifies allocator differences: **rpmalloc** finishes in **~12.2 s** (**2.49×** vs ptmalloc2's ~30.4 s). **snmalloc** (~17.2 s) and **mallocng** (~14.4 s) also beat ptmalloc2 substantially; **mimalloc** is near ptmalloc2 here.
+- Parallel `-j16` is more CPU-bound, but **snmalloc** (~16.26 s) and **jemalloc** (~16.34 s) still edge out ptmalloc2 (~17.76 s); **mallocng** regresses to ~19.8 s from lock contention across 16 clang processes.
+- Peak RSS: ptmalloc2 is leanest; rpmalloc uses the most memory (single-process ~319 MB, parallel tree sum ~5.0 GB).
+- Serial multi-file (`-j1`) mirrors single-process rankings: snmalloc/jemalloc/mimalloc/rpmalloc ~182 s vs glibc 199 s vs mallocng 225 s.
