+
+### Cross-cutting observations
+
+- **C / clang**: jemalloc and snmalloc are consistently among the fastest single-TU times; ptmalloc2 and mallocng trail. Parallel `-j12` favors mimalloc/jemalloc; rpmalloc/snmalloc show higher wall time and RSS under multi-process clang.
+- **C / gcc**: modern allocators help more than with clang on `-O2` SQLite (mimalloc/jemalloc/snmalloc ~18–20 s vs glibc ~28 s). gcc uses substantially more RSS than clang on the same C inputs.
+- **C++ / clang**: mimalloc leads single-TU `-O2` (~17.1 s). Several alternate allocators **lose** on `-O3` C++ versus ptmalloc2 (higher means, large run spreads), suggesting sensitivity to clang’s optimizers’ allocation patterns plus memory pressure.
+- **C++ / gcc**: ptmalloc2 is surprisingly strong on single-TU `-O2`/`-O3` time and leanest RSS, but uses **~1.2–1.3 GB** RSS vs clang’s ~0.55–0.64 GB for the same TU. Parallel C++ `-j12` flips the ranking: **rpmalloc/snmalloc/jemalloc** win wall time while consuming ~14 GB aggregated RSS.
+- **mallocng** remains a poor fit for parallel compiles (global lock) on both compilers, and is rarely best on single-TU C++.
+- Takeaway for compiler workloads: gains are **compiler- and language-specific**. gcc C builds benefit clearly from mimalloc/jemalloc/snmalloc; clang C benefits modestly; clang C++ is mixed; gcc parallel C++ favors snmalloc/rpmalloc at high RSS cost.
