+### Recommendation for this machine
+
+For **clang-first `ninja -j32` on mixed C/C++**, the `-j32` mixed medians are:
+
+| Rank | Backend | Mixed median | Notes |
+|-----:|---------|-------------:|-------|
+| 1 | **rpmalloc** | **70.5 s** | Fastest mixed; also strong on pure C++ (`41.9 s`) and pure C (`28.3 s`). Highest RSS (~17–19 GB tree sum). |
+| 2 | **snmalloc** | **70.7 s** | Ties rpmalloc on mixed; excellent pure C (`28.1 s`). One noisy C++ outlier run (62 s) but median solid. |
+| 3 | **mimalloc** | **71.1 s** | Very close; good single-TU C++ earlier. Pure-C `-j32` showed high variance (40–79 s). |
+| 4 | **jemalloc** | **75.9 s** | Best/most stable pure-C clang `-j32` (`28.9 s`). Slightly behind on mixed. |
+| 5 | glibc ptmalloc2 | **76.8 s** | Baseline; leanest-ish RSS on some cells but leaves ~6–10 s on the table vs top three. |
+| 6 | mallocng | **108.4 s** | Clear loss under multi-process clang (global lock). Avoid for `-j32`. |
+
+**Practical pick:** `--with-malloc=rpmalloc` or `--with-malloc=snmalloc` as the system default for this box. Both beat ptmalloc2 by ~8% on the mixed clang `-j32` proxy and by ~20%+ on pure parallel C++. Prefer **snmalloc** if you also care about single-threaded C++ compile latency stability from earlier single-TU tests; prefer **rpmalloc** if realloc-heavy app runtimes matter (synthetic suite).
+
+For **gcc packages at `-j32`**, rpmalloc (~80.8 s) and mimalloc (~84.2 s) beat glibc’s median (~111.6 s, pulled up by a 135 s outlier). Expect **~33–36 GB** aggregated RSS with gcc `-j32` mixed — fine on 62 GB RAM but tight if other jobs run.
